<p>Vega is building a collection of classic science video lectures given by eminent scientists, both from its own source material, licensing agreements on science videos from universities and other independent groups such as the Feynman family and through links to other high quality video resources.</p><table width="100%"><tr><td class="table_top_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title='<p>Chosen by the New Scientist - best on-line videos 2007. A set of four priceless archival science video recordings from the University of Auckland (New Zealand) of the outstanding Nobel prize-winning physicist Richard Feynman - arguably the greatest science lecturer ever. Although the recording is of modest technical quality the exceptional personal style and unique delivery shine through.</p>' onmouseover="return escape('<p>Chosen by the New Scientist - best on-line videos 2007. A set of four priceless archival science video recordings from the University of Auckland (New Zealand) of the outstanding Nobel prize-winning physicist Richard Feynman - arguably the greatest science lecturer ever. Although the recording is of modest technical quality the exceptional personal style and unique delivery shine through.</p>')" href="../subseries/8"><img height="100"  src="../../images/series_system/150.feynman.jpg_100x100.jpeg" width="100" border="0" /></a></td><td class="table_top_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title='<p>A series of science video lectures from the Royal Institution of Great Britain.&nbsp; The Royal Institution Discourses have been held continuously since 1826 when they were instituted by Michael Faraday as a means of informing the public about the intellectual, economic, social and ethical aspects of science. They remain one of the premier science lecture series world-wide.</p>' onmouseover="return escape('<p>A series of science video lectures from the Royal Institution of Great Britain.&nbsp; The Royal Institution Discourses have been held continuously since 1826 when they were instituted by Michael Faraday as a means of informing the public about the intellectual, economic, social and ethical aspects of science. They remain one of the premier science lecture series world-wide.</p>')" href="../subseries/12"><img height="100"  src="../../images/series_system/150.institution.jpg_100x100.jpeg" width="100" border="0" /></a></td><td class="table_top_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title='<p>Video recordings of lectures from the Royal Society.&nbsp; The Royal Society hosts regular Public Lectures, designed to give a perspective of science in society from leading scientists, writers and broadcasters. Admission is normally free but tickets are required in advance, and more information is available on the Royal Society Web Site.</p>' onmouseover="return escape('<p>Video recordings of lectures from the Royal Society.&nbsp; The Royal Society hosts regular Public Lectures, designed to give a perspective of science in society from leading scientists, writers and broadcasters. Admission is normally free but tickets are required in advance, and more information is available on the Royal Society Web Site.</p>')" href="../subseries/10"><img height="100"  src="../../images/series_system/royalsociety.jpg_100x100.jpeg" width="100" border="0" /></a></td><td class="table_top_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title='<p>A series of science video lectures on astrophysical chemistry by Harry Kroto at Florida State University, 2004.</p>' onmouseover="return escape('<p>A series of science video lectures on astrophysical chemistry by Harry Kroto at Florida State University, 2004.</p>')" href="../subseries/16"><img height="100"  src="../../images/series_system/nasa_universe_150.jpg_100x100.jpeg" width="100" border="0" /></a></td></tr><tr><td class="table_bottom_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title='<p>Chosen by the New Scientist - best on-line videos 2007. A set of four priceless archival science video recordings from the University of Auckland (New Zealand) of the outstanding Nobel prize-winning physicist Richard Feynman - arguably the greatest science lecturer ever. Although the recording is of modest technical quality the exceptional personal style and unique delivery shine through.</p>' onmouseover="return escape('<p>Chosen by the New Scientist - best on-line videos 2007. A set of four priceless archival science video recordings from the University of Auckland (New Zealand) of the outstanding Nobel prize-winning physicist Richard Feynman - arguably the greatest science lecturer ever. Although the recording is of modest technical quality the exceptional personal style and unique delivery shine through.</p>')" href="../subseries/8">Richard Feynman - Science Videos</a></td><td class="table_bottom_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title='<p>A series of science video lectures from the Royal Institution of Great Britain.&nbsp; The Royal Institution Discourses have been held continuously since 1826 when they were instituted by Michael Faraday as a means of informing the public about the intellectual, economic, social and ethical aspects of science. They remain one of the premier science lecture series world-wide.</p>' onmouseover="return escape('<p>A series of science video lectures from the Royal Institution of Great Britain.&nbsp; The Royal Institution Discourses have been held continuously since 1826 when they were instituted by Michael Faraday as a means of informing the public about the intellectual, economic, social and ethical aspects of science. They remain one of the premier science lecture series world-wide.</p>')" href="../subseries/12">Royal Institution Discourses - Science Videos</a></td><td class="table_bottom_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title='<p>Video recordings of lectures from the Royal Society.&nbsp; The Royal Society hosts regular Public Lectures, designed to give a perspective of science in society from leading scientists, writers and broadcasters. Admission is normally free but tickets are required in advance, and more information is available on the Royal Society Web Site.</p>' onmouseover="return escape('<p>Video recordings of lectures from the Royal Society.&nbsp; The Royal Society hosts regular Public Lectures, designed to give a perspective of science in society from leading scientists, writers and broadcasters. Admission is normally free but tickets are required in advance, and more information is available on the Royal Society Web Site.</p>')" href="../subseries/10">Royal Society Public Lectures - Science Videos</a></td><td class="table_bottom_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title='<p>A series of science video lectures on astrophysical chemistry by Harry Kroto at Florida State University, 2004.</p>' onmouseover="return escape('<p>A series of science video lectures on astrophysical chemistry by Harry Kroto at Florida State University, 2004.</p>')" href="../subseries/16">Astrophysical Chemistry Video Lectures by Harry Kroto</a></td></tr><tr><td class="table_top_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title='<p>Four science video lectures from the 2004/5 Toyo University Bio-Nanotechnology Symposiums by Harry Kroto, Akira Tonomura and Derek Woolfson.</p>' onmouseover="return escape('<p>Four science video lectures from the 2004/5 Toyo University Bio-Nanotechnology Symposiums by Harry Kroto, Akira Tonomura and Derek Woolfson.</p>')" href="../subseries/20"><img height="100"  src="../../images/series_system/toyo1.jpg_100x100.jpeg" width="100" border="0" /></a></td><td class="table_top_spacer" valign="top" align="center" width="25%"><a title='<p>A collection of Science Video Lectures by Crutzen, Rowland, Kasha, Veltman and t`Hooft.</p>' onmouseover="return escape('<p>A collection of Science Video Lectures by Crutzen, Rowland, Kasha, Veltman and t`Hooft.</p>')" href="../subseries/46"><img height="100"  src="..